<br>
We made a conscious and deliberate decision to focus on quality of members (with the emphasis on character) rather than on the UBERness of their gear or prior EQ exploits.  With this in mind, we started a rather thorough system of applicants and applications which consist of applying at the website, a guild application email, a personal interview, grouping and raiding with the guild, three reports on the individual's character and skill, and then a guild wide vote requiring at least 50 percent of the total vote.<br>
<br>
The key to keeping the guild running is discipline.  Sure, some people will argue (and their point is valid) that Everquest is a game, nothing more, and they don't want to have to leave their bosses at work and come home to listen to me ordering them around.<br>
<br>
However...<br>
<br>
Everquest is a team game, a guild game, and if it weren't for your guildmates, you'd likely not be where you stand in the game.  You wear a tag above your head for a reason, and the tag stands for something- it means you are an integral part of something larger than just yourself, and should instantly instill a sense of team pride.  So when you commit to joining a guild, you commit to working TOGETHER as a team, and like any team game, you need leadership and you need direction.<br>
<br>
Which brings me to discipline- you need discipline.  Anytime I've backed off on my guildmates fearing I was being too rigid or demanding, I'd see guildmates slouching in GFay doing nothing, unwilling to lift a finger to help someone after exp or finishing off a quest.  So when I let my guild just filter off and do whatever they want, we lost the team/guild focus.<br>
<br>
You need to keep people in line- if this were a fantasy world (hey wait, it is, dammit), people would naturally fall in line and always think with the guild in mind.  But they don't, and that's why you need to keep at them, constantly reminding them (if necessary) of the guilds goals and intentions, and always keep trying to keep the guild moving in a forward, progressive direction instead of merely standing still.<br>
<br>
Only way to do this is by being fair, I think.  Some people you're going to be better friends with in the guild, and some people will get on your nerves- this is inevitable.  The key is to remain fair with everybody no matter what.  Being fair may mean going against what you WANT to do, but maintaining a definitive line of what's right and wrong will keep the guild focused.<br>
<br>
In the end, it depends on where you want your guild to go.  Some guilds crave server worship and the title of &quot;UBER&quot; next to their names.  They want items of prestige, mobs of prestige and so on so they can argue over who's killed such and such more times and with how many people.<br>
<br>
That's all well and good, and props to the guilds able to accomplish the above- it's tough to do.  But other guilds (Covenant of Valor for instance) focuses on the behavior and integrity of its members, avoiding any sort of &quot;level cap&quot; designed to keep a guild's recruits high and strong.<br>
<br>
Personally, I'd much rather have someone on Xev say &quot;FE are nice people&quot; than &quot;FE are leet!&quot;.  We're learning the endgame, having fun with it, and hopefully we'll be able to aid with CR's in the planes instead of merely requesting help time and time again. =)<br>
<br>
But anyway, guild leaders in the mid-levels, I recommend you to be strict and focused.  You may lose a few members, but having a core of disciplined, polite and gracious folks can take you a whole lot farther than a group of greedy, loot-motivated individuals who care about nothing but their own EQ status.  IMHO.<br>
<br>
