<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Warning:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  I'm about to descend into a black pit of autobiography.  The stuff which follows is only really going to be of interest to people who are trying to run a mid-level guild and are looking for thoughts from someone who's done it, or to people who're vaguely interested in the history of &lt;Blood Cult&gt;.  Anyone else is going to find this pretty dull...<br>
<br>
I'm the founder, and former leader, of &lt;Blood Cult&gt;.  In its present form, the guild has existed since the summer of 2001 and I led it for about six months before passing leadership on to Nogi for personal reasons.  I'm still an officer and active participant.<br>
<br>
I was lucky enough to start with some pretty good people on board.  We had all previously been members of the &lt;Blood Cult Clan&gt;, which ceased to exist when its leader went out of contact for over three months.  We'd decided that we all wanted to stay together and make a new guild rather than go our separate ways.<br>
<br>
There were a dozen people in the guild in its first incarnation.  I think the highest level person was about 52, and ranged down to the 30's.  We'd never raided the planes, and our idea of a major raid was to get half a dozen people together and head to Sebilis.<br>
<br>
My initial choice of officers was fairly simple... I chose those people who had been successful officers in &lt;Blood Cult Clan&gt;.  I think there were four officers initially.<br>
<br>
On recruitment, I chose not to have a formal application policy, but I did insist that the officer who invited a new member took responsibility for spending time with, and coaching, that new member.  The officer was also accountable for that new member's actions... so if someone was invited to the guild, and their actions subsequently brought the guild into disrepute, then the officer who invited them took some stick from yours truly.<br>
<br>
(Nowadays, it's a little more challenging to get into &lt;Blood Cult&gt; - but then, we're not exactly a `mid-level guild` any more.  We've got a formal application procedure and a list of requirements which you can view at <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.bloodcult.net.">www.bloodcult.net.</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> )<br>
<br>
The result of this policy was that recruitment was slower than some of the officers would like.  However, it also led to the recruitment of some very good people.  Also our members, by and large, have remained with us and continued to contribute strongly - and it's relatively rare that a guildie's actions reflect badly on &lt;Blood Cult&gt;.  I had practically no disciplinary work to do.<br>
<br>
I delegated the tasks of raid leadership and recruitment/coaching (I feel that recruitment and coaching can't really be separated), but I kept personal control of loot distribution.  I'm glad I did that - the sad fact is, that if there's one issue that causes guilds to argue with each other, it's loot.  I worked on a system of /randoming off most items but reserving a few bits and pieces to award to people who'd made an outstanding contribution to the guild.<br>
<br>
I won't say that was perfect - it still led to disagreements and bad feeling on occasion.  But then, I guess that loot always does.  I'll discuss the three most popular systems of loot distribution below.<br>
<br>
Although I made the majority of strategic decisions personally, I did make sure that I consulted the guild membership where I could, by means of polls on our website or direct discussion.  I wanted to run a guild for the benefit of the membership rather than for the benefit of the leadership, and I think that our members sensed that.  If you look at every successful guild on Xev, you'll see that although the details of how it's run do vary, they are all the same in that the members <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> trust</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> the leadership to run the guild for their benefit.  If that trust ever falters, you're sunk.<br>
<br>
The guild was reasonably successful, and we soon decided that our main focus was on what we saw as the high end of the game (which we defined - don't laugh - as raiding places as uber as the Plane of Growth).  That meant that there was no value in inviting people below level 46 to the guild because they couldn't join in the majority of guild activities.  So we put a minimum level restriction of 46.<br>
<br>
By the time I handed leadership of the guild over to Nogi about six months later, we had about 45 members, several level 60's and several with epics.<br>
<br>
In summary, I found that leading a mid level guild successfully came down to the following five things:-<br>
<br>
1.  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Recruitment and coaching.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  You have to make sure that you only accept reasonably good players into your guild, and you have to ensure that they have someone in the guild who spends time with them developing their abilities further.<br>
<br>
2.  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Raiding.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  A guild that raids together frequently becomes a tight-knit, disciplined force which is greater than the sum of its parts.<br>
<br>
3.  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Dialogue.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  The guild leader makes the final decisions, but the membership is consulted where possible before decisions are made.<br>
<br>
4.  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Trust.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  The membership can see that the leaders are, by and large, working for them rather than the other way around.<br>
<br>
5.  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Loot.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Some people aren't motivated by loot, but many people are, and those people to whom loot matters feel that their chances of getting the items they want are enhanced rather than diminished by their membership of the guild.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>The three main methods of loot distribution</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--></b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Every method of loot distribution has its dedicated supporters.  They all have upsides and downsides - but you do need a clear policy on how it's done.<br>
<br>
I'm not going into a discussion of NBG (`Need Before Greed`) or CAWU (`Can And Will Use`) here.  These are very slippery subjects and you usually see them used as arguments by people who want to exclude others from having a chance at receiving an item.  Every guild which employs these concepts needs to establish detailed principles on precisely what they mean and how they can be employed.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Random:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Generally items are /randomed off.  It's for the individual to decide whether or not they roll - sometimes people may choose to `pass` on a roll, for various reasons.  In some variations, once someone has won one roll, they are expected to pass until everyone else on the raid has received a drop.<br>
<br>
This method can lead to someone who has made a big contribution to the guild being passed over in favour of someone else who has not made such a big contribution.  However, it has the benefit that it is seen to be fair - the leaders cannot be accused of arbitrarily assigning items to themselves.  It also means that people who attend the most raids are statistically likely to receive the most loot.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Leader assigns:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  The guild leader, raid leader or other loot distribution officer decides who receives items.<br>
<br>
Where the loot distribution officer is trustworthy, this system is certain to give the greatest rewards to the people who make the greatest contribution.  However, it has the drawback that it can lead to accusations of the leaders assigning the best items to themselves.  For this reason it can lead to arguments and bad feeling, particularly in situations where the leaders have not yet proved beyond all doubt that they can be trusted.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> DKP:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Guild members earn points (DKP stands for Dragon Kill Points) by participating in guild activities.  They can then spend those points to `buy` loot.<br>
<br>
In practise this system faces challenges about which items are worth which amount of points, and there is also the problem of several people wanting to buy the same item.  Sometimes people can accumulate very large amounts of points without being able to spend them - and with some DKP systems, uber items can rot because nobody wants to pay the points cost for them.  Finally, the amount of record-keeping required can become very large.<br>
<br>
Famously, the uber guild &lt;Afterlife&gt; use the DKP system heavily.  By contrast, &lt;Fires of Heaven&gt; are on record as describing DKP as `gay`.<br>
<br>
In summary, there is no perfect method of loot distribution and I've found that it's best to use a mixture of methods depending upon the drop and the raid.<br>
<br>
Shadowfrost <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#deddbf><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub12.ezboard.com/upentorian.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Pentorian</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Visiting poster. Post MORE :)</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#330000>(4/6/02 10:53 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub228.ezboard.com/fxevserverboardsfrm12.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Running a Mid-level Guild</span><hr size=1> Shadowfrost..<br>
