<br>
1. Expect to do a LOT of the work yourself. <br>
<br>
Obviously you should deligate as much responsibility as possible onto your other officers as well, to keep you sane, but you will still have to carry the majority of the workload yourself.<br>
<br>
2. Choose your officers carefully.<br>
<br>
If you are just a casual group of people, this isn't very important, but if you aim to go beyond the Hate/Fear/epics stage of the game, you are going to need strong, intelligent officers who can take charge of a situation. No matter how dedicated you are, SOMETHING is bound to come up while you are offline and it is up to your officers to lead in your place.<br>
<br>
3. Guild resources must be communal to be effective.<br>
<br>
(Disclaimer - This is in direct opposition to the current EULA) Resources such as guild banks, scouts and porters should be available for use by several, if not all officers. If a_porter04 goes to visit thier brother in Iowa for a week and he's the only one in the guild who can port to Cobalt Scar, you are crippled. Likewise, accounts with scouts on them (and don't pretend you don't know what scouts are for, everyone uses them) should be accessable by at least all of the officers.<br>
<br>
4. Know thy enemy.<br>
<br>
There is a lot of competition at the mid level on our server. As it stands now, any group of 65's can drop in and kill Kunark dragons fairly easily. Even some important Velious mobs are doable with 1 group (or in some cases, less). Keep an eye on what the competition is doing. If 30 members of a_guild06 show up in an underused zone like DN, you know they aren't there for a picnic.<br>
<br>
5. Trust is built through fairness and discipline.<br>
<br>
Regardless of what your own guild's rules may be, apply them to everyone evenly, INCLUDING YOURSELF. If your members feel that certain members of your guild are recieving special treatment or are being singled out for extra punishment, they won't trust you. Sun Tzu said it best:<br>
<br>
